Optimizing the Dataset Pipeline for Faster Training

Before feeding images into the model, we improve the dataset performance using:

  • cache() Stores images in memory after the first read.
    • Speeds up every following epoch.
  • shuffle(1000) (training only)
    • Ensures batches come in a random order, which improves generalization.
  • prefetch(AUTOTUNE)
    Lets TensorFlow prepare the next batch while the model is still training on the current batch.
    • Overlaps preprocessing + model execution = faster training.

We apply different strategies per split:

  • train_ds cache shuffle prefetch
  • val_ds cache prefetch
  • test_ds cache prefetch

This keeps training fast and evaluation stable.

In[6]:
# --- Optimize datasets for performance ---

# For the training set:
# 1. cache()      keeps preprocessed images in memory after first pass (faster)
# 2. shuffle()    adds randomness to training order (important for learning)
# 3. prefetch()   overlaps data loading with model execution (improves GPU/CPU utilization)
train_ds = train_ds.cache().shuffle(1000).prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)

# Validation set:
# - We do NOT shuffle (evaluation must stay ordered and consistent)
# - cache() + prefetch() improves reading speed
val_ds = val_ds.cache().prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)

# Test set:
# - Same logic as validation: no shuffling, only caching + prefetching
test_ds = test_ds.cache().prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)

Dataset Pipeline Optimized

The training, validation, and test datasets are now wrapped in a high-performance input pipeline:

  • Training data is cached, shuffled, and prefetched
    • ideal for stable and efficient learning
  • Validation and test sets use caching + prefetching
    • ensures fast, deterministic evaluation

These optimizations significantly reduce bottlenecks during model training, especially for deep networks like VGG16.

Model 1 Vanilla CNN

In this section, we implement a lightweight Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) trained entirely from scratch to classify images of cats and dogs. This model serves as our baseline, helping us compare traditional CNN performance against transfer learning (VGG16).

The architecture includes:

  • Convolution + Max-Pooling blocks for feature extraction
  • ReLU activations for non-linearity
  • Dropout layers to reduce overfitting
  • A compact Dense classifier head for binary output

We also apply essential preprocessing steps:

  • Input rescaling (pixel values 0255 01)
  • Mild data augmentation to improve generalization
  • Callbacks for early stopping and saving the best performing model

This vanilla CNN establishes a strong baseline before introducing the more powerful VGG16 transfer learning model.

Data Preprocessing and Augmentation Layers

Before training the vanilla CNN, we define the preprocessing steps that will be applied to all input images. These layers help standardize the data and improve the models robustness.

We use:

  • Random data augmentation
    • This introduces small variations (flips, rotations, zooms) that help the model generalize better to new images.
  • Rescaling
    • Pixel values are normalized from 0255 to 01, which stabilizes and speeds up training.

The following code block defines the augmentation pipeline and the rescaling layer that will be inserted at the start of our CNN model.

In[9]:
# --- Data preprocessing & augmentation layers ---

# Random data augmentation to make the model more robust
data_augmentation = keras.Sequential(
    [
        layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),         # flip images horizontally
        layers.RandomRotation(0.05),             # small random rotations
        layers.RandomZoom(0.1),                  # small random zoom
    ],
    name="data_augmentation",
)

# Rescaling layer to normalize pixel values from [0, 255]  [0, 1]
rescale = layers.Rescaling(1.0 / 255, name="rescale_layer")

Interpretation

This preprocessing block ensures that our vanilla CNN receives clean, normalized, and more diverse input data:

  • RandomFlip, RandomRotation, and RandomZoom simulate natural variations in real-world pet photos, helping the model avoid overfitting.
  • Rescaling reduces pixel intensity values to a smaller, consistent range, which improves training stability and prevents overly large gradients.
  • Using Keras preprocessing layers means that augmentation happens on the fly, directly on the GPU/CPU pipeline, without modifying the dataset on disk.

Together, these steps form a strong preprocessing foundation for training the CNN effectively.

Building Model 1 Vanilla CNN

In this section, we define the full architecture of our baseline convolutional neural network (CNN). This model is trained entirely from scratch, learning image features directly from the Dogs vs Cats dataset.

The architecture includes:

  • Input Augmentation Rescaling
    • Ensures data normalization and improved generalization.
  • Three convolution + max-pooling blocks
    • Extract spatial features at increasing abstraction levels.
  • A dense classification head
    • Converts learned features into a binary prediction.
  • Dropout (0.5)
    • Reduces overfitting by preventing co-adaptation of neurons.

The model is compiled using:

  • Adam optimizer
  • Binary cross-entropy loss
  • Accuracy metric

Once built, we display a full summary of all layers, output shapes, and parameter counts.

In[10]:
# --- Function to build the vanilla CNN model ---

def build_vanilla_cnn(input_shape=IMG_SIZE + (3,)):
    """
    Build a simple CNN model for binary classification (cats vs dogs).

    Architecture:
    - Data augmentation + rescaling
    - 3 convolution + max-pooling blocks
    - Dropout for regularization
    - Dense layer with sigmoid for binary output
    """
    model = keras.Sequential(
        [
            # Input layer expects images of shape (height, width, 3 channels)
            layers.Input(shape=input_shape),

            # Apply data augmentation only during training
            data_augmentation,

            # Normalize pixel values to [0, 1]
            rescale,

            # --- Block 1: Conv + MaxPool ---
            layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same"),
            layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),

            # --- Block 2: Conv + MaxPool ---
            layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same"),
            layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),

            # --- Block 3: Conv + MaxPool ---
            layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same"),
            layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),

            # Flatten the feature maps into a 1D vector
            layers.Flatten(),

            # Dense layer with some capacity
            layers.Dense(128, activation="relu"),

            # Dropout to reduce overfitting
            layers.Dropout(0.5),

            # Final output layer:
            # - 1 unit + sigmoid activation for binary classification
            layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"),
        ],
        name="vanilla_cnn",
    )

    # Compile the model with binary cross-entropy loss
    model.compile(
        optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(),
        loss="binary_crossentropy",
        metrics=["accuracy"],
    )

    return model


# Build and summarize the CNN model
cnn_model = build_vanilla_cnn()
cnn_model.summary()

Interpretation of the Vanilla CNN Architecture

The model summary confirms that our vanilla CNN is structured and functioning exactly as intended. Below is a breakdown of each major component:

  • Preprocessing Layer (0 parameters):

    The model begins with:

    • data_augmentation
    • rescale_layer

    These layers ensure that:

    • Images are normalized to the [0, 1] range
    • Light augmentations (flip, rotation, zoom) apply only during training
    • No extra parameters are added to the model size

    This improves generalization without increasing computational cost.

  • Three convolutional blocks:

    These blocks extract increasingly complex visual features: | Block | Filters | Output Shape | Purpose | | ---------------- | ------- | -------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ | | Conv Block 1 | 32 | (180, 180, 32) | Detects edges, corners, basic textures | | Conv Block 2 | 64 | (90, 90, 64) | Learns patterns such as fur edges, shapes | | Conv Block 3 | 128 | (45, 45, 128) | Higher-level visual features (face shapes, ears, eyes) |

    Each block uses:

    • ReLU activation
    • MaxPooling2D to reduce spatial size while keeping important features

  • Flatten & Dense feature layer:

    • The Flatten layer converts feature maps into a long vector of 61,952 units.

  • Dropout Layer (rate = 0.5)

    A dropout of 50% helps reduce overfitting, which is important because:

    • The dataset has 5,000 images
    • The fully connected layer has many parameters

    This improves stability and generalization.

  • Output Layer (Binary Classification)

    The final Dense layer:

    • Has 1 neuron
    • Uses sigmoid activation
    • Outputs a probability for the dog class
      • 0 = cat
      • 1 = dog

Training the Vanilla CNN Callbacks & Model Fitting

Before training the vanilla CNN, we configure two important callbacks:

  • ModelCheckpoint
    • Saves the best version of the model (highest validation accuracy).
    • Ensures we do not lose the best epoch even if later epochs overfit.
  • EarlyStopping
    • Monitors validation loss.
    • Stops training if performance stops improving (patience = 3).
    • Automatically restores weights from the best epoch.

Together, these callbacks prevent overfitting and keep training efficient.

In this section, we:

  • Create a models/ directory to store saved models.
  • Train the CNN for up to 20 epochs.
  • Let callbacks decide the ideal stopping point.

The training log printed in the output will show:

  • When a best model is saved
  • When validation accuracy improves
  • When early stopping triggers
In[11]:
# --- Callbacks: save best model and stop early if overfitting ---

# Directory to store trained models
MODELS_DIR = PROJECT_ROOT / "models"
MODELS_DIR.mkdir(exist_ok=True)

cnn_checkpoint_path = MODELS_DIR / "cnn_dogs_vs_cats_best.keras"

cnn_checkpoint_cb = keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
    filepath=cnn_checkpoint_path,
    monitor="val_accuracy",
    save_best_only=True,
    mode="max",
    verbose=1,
)

cnn_earlystop_cb = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(
    monitor="val_loss",
    patience=3,
    restore_best_weights=True,
    verbose=1,
)

# --- Auto-load best CNN model if it exists (skip retraining) ---

import pickle

saved_model = cnn_checkpoint_path  # same path as checkpoint

if saved_model.exists():
    print("Saved CNN model found  loading from disk and skipping training.")
    cnn_model = keras.models.load_model(saved_model)
    cnn_model_loaded = True
else:
    print("No saved CNN model found  training from scratch.")
    cnn_model_loaded = False

# --- Train the vanilla CNN model (only if needed) ---

if not cnn_model_loaded:
    print("Training CNN model...")
    history_cnn = cnn_model.fit(
        train_ds,
        epochs=EPOCHS_CNN,
        validation_data=val_ds,
        callbacks=[cnn_checkpoint_cb, cnn_earlystop_cb],
    )

    # After training, load the best checkpoint saved by ModelCheckpoint
    cnn_model = keras.models.load_model(saved_model)

    # Optionally save training history so plots work without retraining
    with open(PROJECT_ROOT / "history_cnn.pkl", "wb") as f:
        pickle.dump(history_cnn.history, f)

else:
    print("Skipping CNN training  using saved CNN model.")

    # Try loading saved history so plot_training_history() still works
    hist_path = PROJECT_ROOT / "history_cnn.pkl"
    if hist_path.exists():
        with open(hist_path, "rb") as f:
            history_data = pickle.load(f)

        class Obj:  # tiny fake History-like object
            pass

        history_cnn = Obj()
        history_cnn.history = history_data

        print("Loaded saved CNN training history.")
    else:
        print("No saved training history found  plots will be empty until you train once.")
        class Obj:
            pass
        history_cnn = Obj()
        history_cnn.history = {
            "accuracy": [],
            "val_accuracy": [],

            "val_loss": [],
        }

Training Curves Vanilla CNN

To understand how well the vanilla CNN learned over 20 epochs, we visualize two key metrics:

  • Training vs Validation Accuracy
  • Training vs Validation Loss

These curves help us evaluate:

  • Whether the model is learning steadily
  • Whether overfitting occurs (large gap between training and validation)

We use a utility function that extracts the metrics from the Keras History object and plots them side-by-side for clear interpretation.

In[12]:
# --- Utility function to plot training history ---


def plot_training_history(history, title_prefix="Vanilla CNN"):
    """
    Plot training vs validation accuracy and loss from a Keras History object.
    """

    # Extract metrics from the history object
    acc = history.history.get("accuracy", [])
    val_acc = history.history.get("val_accuracy", [])
    loss = history.history.get("loss", [])
    val_loss = history.history.get("val_loss", [])

    epochs_range = range(1, len(acc) + 1)

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))

    # --- Accuracy subplot ---
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, acc, label="Train Accuracy")
    plt.plot(epochs_range, val_acc, label="Val Accuracy")
    plt.title(f"{title_prefix}  Accuracy")
    plt.xlabel("Epoch")
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.legend()

    # --- Loss subplot ---
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, loss, label="Train Loss")
    plt.plot(epochs_range, val_loss, label="Val Loss")
    plt.title(f"{title_prefix}  Loss")

PrecisionRecall Curve (Vanilla CNN)

To further evaluate the vanilla CNNs classification behavior, we compute a precisionrecall (PR) curve using the raw prediction probabilities.

Why PR Curve?

  • It shows how the models precision and recall trade off as the decision threshold changes.
  • It is especially useful for imbalanced datasets or when false positives vs false negatives have different costs.
  • Unlike accuracy, the PR curve focuses solely on the models ability to correctly score the positive class.

In this step, we collect all predicted probabilities on the test set and use
precision_recall_curve from scikit-learn to generate the curve.

VGG16 Preprocessing & Data Augmentation (Setup)

In this section, we prepare the preprocessing steps required for training the VGG16 transfer learning model. VGG16 expects images to be preprocessed in a specific way (mean subtraction using ImageNet statistics), so we wrap the preprocess_input function inside a Keras Lambda layer to integrate it into the model pipeline.

We also define a dedicated augmentation block for VGG16, similar to the vanilla CNN, to introduce variability and improve generalization during training.

In[19]:
# --- VGG16: Preprocessing and Data Augmentation ---

from tensorflow.keras.applications.vgg16 import preprocess_input

# VGG16 expects images preprocessed with its own function.
# We will wrap preprocess_input inside a Keras layer so it fits into the model.

preprocess_layer = layers.Lambda(preprocess_input, name="vgg16_preprocess")

# Data augmentation to improve generalization
vgg16_augmentation = keras.Sequential([
    layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
    layers.RandomRotation(0.05),
    layers.RandomZoom(0.1),
], name="vgg16_data_augmentation")

Summary VGG16 Preprocessing & Augmentation

This cell prepares all input-processing components needed for VGG16:

  • preprocess_input wrapped in a Lambda layer ensures that every image is automatically transformed according to VGG16s ImageNet normalization rules.
  • Data augmentation (flip, rotation, zoom) provides extra variability, helping the model adapt to different lighting, orientation, and pose conditions in the catsdogs dataset.
  • Keeping preprocessing and augmentation as separate layers makes the full pipeline modular, reusable, and fully compatible with Keras functional API.

These components will be inserted at the front of the VGG16 model architecture so that all images entering the feature extractor are correctly normalized and enhanced for training.

Loading the VGG16 Base Model (Feature Extractor)

In this step, we load the pretrained VGG16 network using ImageNet weights. Because we are using transfer learning, we remove the fully connected classification head (include_top=False) and keep only the convolutional blocks, which act as a powerful feature extractor.

We also freeze all convolutional layers, ensuring that during the first phase of training only our custom classifier layers will update this prevents overfitting and keeps training efficient.

This cell prints the full VGG16 architecture so we can verify the layer shapes, parameter counts, and confirm that the model is completely frozen.

# --- Build Fine-Tuned VGG16 Model ---

inputs = keras.Input(shape=IMG_SIZE + (3,), name="input_image")

x = vgg16_augmentation(inputs)     # Apply augmentation
x = preprocess_layer(x)            # Preprocess using VGG16's rules

x = vgg_base(x, training=False)    # Pass through VGG16 base in inference mode
x = layers.Flatten()(x)

# Add custom classifier head
x = layers.Dense(256, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)  # binary classification

vgg16_model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs, name="vgg16_finetuned")

# Compile
vgg16_model.compile(
    optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-4),
    loss="binary_crossentropy",
    metrics=["accuracy"]
)

vgg16_model.summary()

VGG16 Callbacks Checkpointing & Early Stopping

Before training the VGG16 fine-tuned model, we define two important callbacks:

  • ModelCheckpoint
    Saves the model only when validation accuracy improves.
    This ensures we always keep the best-performing version of the network.

  • EarlyStopping
    Stops training when validation accuracy stops improving for a set number of epochs
    (patience = 5).
    Also restores the weights from the best epoch to avoid overfitting.

These callbacks help stabilize training and prevent unnecessary computation, especially because VGG16 is a heavier model than the vanilla CNN.

In[22]:
# --- Callbacks + Auto-load for VGG16 training ---

from tensorflow.keras.applications.vgg16 import preprocess_input
import pickle

# Path to best VGG16 model checkpoint
vgg16_ckpt_path = PROJECT_ROOT / "models" / "vgg16_dogs_vs_cats_best.keras"
vgg16_ckpt_path.parent.mkdir(exist_ok=True)

# Callback: save best VGG16 model
vgg_checkpoint = keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
    filepath=vgg16_ckpt_path,
    save_best_only=True,
    monitor="val_accuracy",
    mode="max",
    verbose=1,
)

# Callback: early stopping
vgg_earlystop = keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(
    monitor="val_accuracy",
    patience=5,

Interpretation VGG16 Training Callbacks Initialized

The callbacks were set up correctly for the VGG16 fine-tuning stage:

  • ModelCheckpoint

    • Saves the best model to: models/vgg16_dogs_vs_cats_best.keras
    • Tracks validation accuracy (monitor="val_accuracy")
    • Ensures only the strongest model is stored (save_best_only=True)

  • EarlyStopping

    • Monitors validation accuracy and stops training when no improvement is seen for 5 epochs
    • The best weights are automatically restored (restore_best_weights=True)

Together, these callbacks ensure that:

  • Training does not continue unnecessarily
  • Overfitting is minimized
  • The final model used for evaluation is the best-performing checkpoint

This prepares the notebook for efficient and reliable VGG16 training.

Final Discussion Vanilla CNN vs Fine-Tuned VGG16

Model Comparison: Vanilla CNN vs VGG16

The vanilla CNN is a lightweight 8M-parameter model trained entirely from scratch on the 5,000-image dataset. While it successfully learns simple edges, colors, and textures, its representational power is limited. In contrast, VGG16 uses a deeply layered convolutional backbone pre-trained on ImageNet, giving it access to rich high-level features such as shape, contour, texture, and object parts.

This difference is clearly reflected in performance:

  • Vanilla CNN Test Accuracy: 0.756
  • VGG16 Test Accuracy: 0.972

The performance gap demonstrates the effectiveness of transfer learning, especially when training data is limited.

Why VGG16 Performs Better

VGG16 begins with millions of pre-learned filters that capture:

  • edges
  • color gradients
  • shapes
  • textures
  • object-specific structures

Only the classifier head (~3.27M parameters) is trained. This: * reduces overfitting * stabilizes training * avoids learning dataset-specific noise * allows the model to focus on classification boundaries

As a result, VGG16 achieves dramatically stronger generalization.

Overfitting Behavior

Vanilla CNN

  • Training accuracy increases steadily
  • Validation accuracy fluctuates
  • Validation loss shows mild instability
  • Indicates moderate overfitting
  • Struggles with difficult cases:
    • dark cats
    • cluttered backgrounds
    • unusual poses

VGG16

  • Training and validation curves almost overlap
  • Very small trainvalidation gap
  • Early stopping stabilizes performance
  • Shows excellent generalization and minimal overfitting

This validates that freezing the convolutional base + using mild augmentation is effective.

Precision and Recall Interpretation

Vanilla CNN:

  • Cat: Precision ~0.78, Recall ~0.69
  • Cat: Precision ~0.78, Recall ~0.69
  • Indicates frequent mistakes on cat images
  • Lower recall for dogs suggests confusion with cat features in low contrast

VGG16:

  • Precision and recall both 0.970.98 for both classes
  • Very few false positives or false negatives
  • Much more confident and consistent predictions

This reinforces the value of using pretrained deep features.
